  abstract = {Although the concept of a single resource plays an important role in ecological theory, there has been relatively little discussion of what characterizes distinct resources. I argue that distinct resources may be recognized by two properties: (a) the population level of one is not a function solely of the population level of the other, and (b) there exist consumers and environments such that either consumer fitness or total amount of resource consumed depends on the relative amounts of the two resource types. Three simple models are used to explore the implications of these properties. It is impossible to count resources without making assumptions about the discriminations (between different resource items and the places they become available) that can be made by resource consumers. It nevertheless seems very likely that the number of distinct resources is much greater than the number of consumer species in most biological communities. The idea that plants utilize a much smaller number of resources than animals is questioned, and alternative definitions of "distinct resource" applied in several recent theoretical works are criticized.},
